<TITLE> 56 convicted, 4 acquitted in Satkhira verdict </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Satkhira, Apr 19 (bdnews24.com)  The special court in Satkhira has convicted 56 out of the 60 BDR members accused of mutiny. Four riflesmen were acquitted. Outgoing BDR director general Maj Gen Mainul Islam, head of the panel of judges, delivered the verdict on Monday at the special court, located at 7 Rifles Battalion headquarters. The court sentenced 24 of the men to the maximum penalty of seven years imprisonment. This follows earlier verdicts returned in three other special BDR courts in Panchagarh, Thakurgaon and Feni. The accused were charged with rebelling on Feb 26 in support of their comrades in Pilkhana, Dhaka where the rebellion of Feb 25-26, 2009 saw about 70 people dead, including 57 army officers deputed to the BDR. Sixteen of the accused riflesmen admitted their guilt when the procedure began on Dec 7 last year. The trial ended on Mar 23. On Nov 15, the government formed six special courts, including two in Dhaka, to try about 3,500 border guards accused in some 40 cases around the country. bd
